allenge readers to consider how factors such as race, gender, class, and marital status shaped women's lives and influenced their job options, family arrangements, and leisure activities. Breadwinning Daughters brings to light previously forgotten and unstudied experiences and illustrates how women found various ways to negotiate the burdens and joys of the 1930s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDepressionsx1929xOntarioxToronto. 0aDepressionsy1929zOntariozToronto. 0aSingle womenxEmploymentxHistoryx20th centuryxOntarioxToronto. 0aSingle womenxEmploymentzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen employeesxEconomic conditionsx20th centuryxOntarioxToronto. 0aWomen employeesxHistoryx20th centuryxOntarioxToronto. 0aWomen employeesxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxOntarioxToronto. 0aWomen employeeszOntariozTorontoxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aWomen employeeszOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen employeeszOntariozTorontoxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aYoung womenxEmploymentxHistoryx20th centuryxOntarioxToronto. 0aYoung womenxEmploymentzOntariozTorontoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268525340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685253423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685253.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK